There is an example code in official documentation showing the case of using delegation:

    interface Base {
        fun print()
    }
    
    class BaseImpl(val x: Int) : Base {
        override fun print() { print(x) }
    }
    
    class Derived(b: Base) : Base by b
    
    fun main() {
        val b = BaseImpl(10)
        Derived(b).print()
    }

Maybe it is more clear for you if you rewrite the same code in Java:

    class BaseImpl implements Base {
    
        private final int x;
    
        public void print() {
            System.out.print(x);
        }
    
        BaseImpl(int x) {
            this.x = x;
        }
    }
    
    class Derived implements Base {
    
        private final Base delegate;
    
        Derived(Base b) {
            this.delegate = b;
        }
    
        public void print() {
            this.delegate.print();
        }
    }
    
    interface Base {
        void print();
    }
    
    public class Test {
    
        public static void main(String[] var0) {
            BaseImpl b = new BaseImpl(10);
            new Derived(b).print();
        }
    }

Now idea of using keyword &#39;by&#39; in Kotlin for delegation is more clear. If you compare Derived class written in Kotlin and the same class written in Java then we see that we don&#39;t need to write boilerplate code such as:

    public void print() {
        this.delegate.print();
    }

It is a simple example where Base class has only one method. Imagine if there are a lot of methods, in Java you must rewrite each methods for just delegation behavior, in Kotlin you should just declare delegation using keyword &#39;by&#39;.

